notesStmt.note: This small copy of the Qur'an was penned by an anonymous scribe in Iran in the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth century CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Arabic. The secondary language of this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.title: al-Qurʾān
القرآن
msItem.note: Fols.1b-2a contains an index of chapters

msItem.title: Prayers and rules for the recitation of the Qur’an
msItem.note: Main text is followed by various prayers and rules for the recitation of the Qur’an (al-aḥkām al-tajwīdīyah), abbreviations for pauses (rumūz al-waqf), names of seven reciters, etc. (all in Arabic and Persian, fols. 190a-211a).

handDesc.handNote: Black vocalized naskh, chapter-headings in red riqāʿ on gold background.

decoDesc.decoNote: Double-frontispiece (fols. 2b-3a) containing a prayer arranged in the form of two medallions with pendants (black, red, and blue ink). Double-page opening decoration (fols. 5b-6a) with text of the first chapter and the beginning of the second.

binding.p: Original nineteenth-century lacquer binding (without flap), with floral design painted on gold ground. Doublures show an all-over pattern of five-petaled flowers painted in gold on a red ground.

history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters' bequest
